  "prompt": "What is the average CPF cash balance for a member at the age of 55 in Singapore?",
  "response": "The Central Provident Fund (CPF) in Singapore is a comprehensive social security savings plan that helps Singaporeans and Permanent Residents fund their retirement, healthcare, and housing needs. The CPF balance for a member at the age of 55 can vary widely depending on factors such as their income, contribution rates, and how they've utilized their CPF funds for housing, healthcare, or other purposes.\n\nAs of recent data, the **average CPF balance for members aged 55** is around **$170,000 to $200,000** in their Ordinary Account (OA), Special Account (SA), and Medisave Account (MA) combined. However, this is an estimate, and individual balances can differ significantly based on personal circumstances.\n\nAt age 55, CPF members are eligible to withdraw their CPF savings after setting aside the **Retirement Sum** in their Retirement Account (RA). The Retirement Sum can be the Basic Retirement Sum (BRS), Full Retirement Sum (FRS), or Enhanced Retirement Sum (ERS), depending on their retirement needs.\n\nFor the most accurate and up-to-date information, refer to the **CPF Board's official website** or statements, as individual balances depend on specific contributions, investments, and withdrawals over time.",
